<section id="why-yoga" class="yoga">
    <div class="container">

        <div class="section-title">
            <span>Why Yoga</span>
            <h2>Why Yoga</h2>
            <p>
                There are many schools of yoga and many explanations about what yoga is and isn’t.
            </p>
            <p>
                While it can be fun to see adverts and instagram posts of (usually conventionally beautiful!) people in seemingly impossible contortions (and we may choose to selectively and mindfully explore accessible variations ourselves!), most of the yoga I do and teach at fifty focuses on simple movements. In classes, we explore the natural range of motion of the spine, neck, shoulders, hips and legs.
            </p>
            <p>
                The yoga postures (also known as asanas), I practice and teach are generally referred to as Hatha yoga, and combine a mix of stretches and postures (often gentle, sometimes with more challenging options), flowing movements (Vinyasa flow), longer holds (Yin yoga) and relaxing supported poses (Restorative yoga).

            </p>
            <p>
                With practice, these physical movements and spending time in stillness, together with some breathwork and perhaps meditation, help us to regain and maintain physical flexibility in our joints and muscles.
            </p>

            <p>This type of yoga practice can help us to become more aware of and more at ease in our bodies. Over time, we may feel stronger, more flexible and more comfortable in everyday life .. to enjoy simple pleasures like walking up hills and over stiles, playing other sports, reaching for things on the top shelf and sleeping comfortably at night.</p>
            <p>People often start practising yoga, drawn by the physical benefits of flexibility and strength. Over time they may find they enjoy and appreciate the breathwork (pranayama) and mindfulness or meditation (dharana/dhyana), which form part of what differentiates yoga from other valuable (done well) movement practices, like gym work-outs, studio classes or pilates.</p>
            <p>Ultimately practising yoga may help us to feel more at ease, not only in our bodies, but in our heads and in life in general. We may experience more mental quanimity with others and with the world around us. We find it easier to observe, to accept and be, rather than needing to do, to make happen and to control.</p>
            <p>Over the past 15 years of regular yoga practice, I have explored many different styles of yoga with teachers in London and elsewhere. I am particularly grateful to Kate, Catherine and James as mentioned above, as well as Aki Omori, Erika Tourell and Norman Blair for their classes and teachings.</p>



        </div>



    </div>

