<section id="about" class="about">
    <div class="container">

        <div class="section-title">
            <span>About Me</span>
            <h2>About Me</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="image d-flex align-items-stretch justify-content-center justify-content-lg-start"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="d-flex flex-column align-items-stretch">
                <div class="content ps-lg-8 d-flex flex-column justify-content-center">
                    <div class="row" style="padding-top: 1em">
                        <p>I first tried yoga in the early 2000s at gym-based classes when I was working in an office job in London. Yoga felt complementary to other sports I was doing then (triathlons and gym work-outs) and an antidote to long days in the office. But ultimately, I found I enjoyed the feeling of stretching, of being in my body and the sense of deep physical and mental relaxation, both during and after each class.</p>
                        <p>It might sound evangelical, but I grew to love yoga. I started to practise more regularly (a few times a week rather than just once) and went on yoga holidays/retreats with a few different teachers. I think (details now blurred in the mists of time) it was my husband who asked me in late 2011 or early 2012 if I might do a yoga teacher training course. I quickly decided that it was a great idea and, spoiled for choice in London, started a 2-year 400-hour teacher training (TT) course with Triyoga in the Summer of 2012.</p>
                        <p>I loved the TT course at Triyoga, with experienced teachers Kate Ellis and Catherine Annis, and will forever be grateful for their expert guidance, as well as the yoga philosophy I learned from from Carlos Poneda and yoga anatomy from Chris Swain. I was then fortunate to have the opportunity to rejoin the Triyoga course from 2014-2016 as a teaching assistant.</p>
                        <p>Although I was still working in an office job, I continued practising, teaching and learning about yoga from 2016-2020. One highlight was a 18-month course with Kate Ellis focused on “Teaching Yoga one-to-one”, also drawing on Kate’s work in Embodied Relational Yoga Therapy. I attended many insightful multi-day workshops, including with Donna Farhi, Richard Rosen, Matthew Sanford, John Stirk and Sally Kempton. I also fell into a happy rhythm of going on retreat twice a year with inspiring and gifted Spanish-based teacher James Jewell.</p>
                        <p>During the pandemic and lockdowns of 2020-2021, my practice was exclusively home-based, and I was grateful for both my own home practice and for the wealth of video classes on YouTube (which get easier to navigate when you know who’s who and what you’re looking for !). I also taught Zoom classes to friends and invited donations to charities of their choice. I was grateful for the connection to yoga and to others.</p>
                        <p>In 2024, a decade after completing my first Teacher Training and with the support of some special people I’ve met at Pythouse Tennis Club in Hatch, I am now exploring teaching yoga as my primary profession. It feels exciting, a little scary, and just right. If my story and the yoga I talk about on this website speak to you, I would love to meet you on the mat soon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
